<DOC><DOCNO> AP900517-0294 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-90 2309EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Navistar     05-17 0182</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Earns-Navistar,0190</SECOND><HEAD>Reports 77 Percent Drop In Quarterly Net</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Navistar International Corp. said net incomeplunged 77 percent in its fiscal second quarter because of anindustry-wide decline in retail truck sales.   Chicago-based Navistar, the country's biggest manufacturer ofmedium- and heavy-duty trucks, said net income in the three monthsended April 30 was $8 million or 1 cent a share, compared with $35million or 11 cents a share in the same period a year ago.   Sales fell 10 percent to $1 billion from $1.1 billion.   Chairman James C. Cotting said industry-wide sales of medium andheavy trucks in North America fell 12 percent in the first threemonths of 1990 to 71,000 units.   Navistar's fiscal second-quarter deliveries of 22,200 units were10 percent below the same quarter a year earlier, Cotting said in astatement.   For the first half of fiscal 1990, Navistar lost $10 million or10 cents a share on sales of $1.9 billion. In the comparable 1989period, the company earned $72 million or 23 cents a share on salesof $2.2 billion.</TEXT></DOC>